Define output directory structure\n33: - [ ] Define target groups (build, test, lint, clean, etc.)\n34: - [ ] Define help target structure with descriptions\n35: - [ ] Design variable override mechanism (environment variables, command line)\n36: - [ ] Document Makefile structure in comments\n37: \n38: **Verification**: Clear, well-documented Makefile structure with all necessary variables defined\n39: \n40: ---\n41: \n42: ### Task 3: Implement help target\n43: - [ ] Create help target as default goal (.DEFAULT_GOAL := help)\n44: - [ ] Implement help text with color coding (BLUE, GREEN, YELLOW, NC)\n45: - [ ] Extract target descriptions from makefile comments\n46: - [ ] Display all available targets with descriptions\n47: - [ ] Display configurable variables with default values\n48: - [ ] Ensure help target is readable and well-formatted\n49: - [ ] Test help target: `make help`\n50: - [ ] Verify all targets are listed\n51: - [ ] Verify all variables are shown\n52: - [ ] Add usage examples in help text\n53: \n54: **Verification**: `make help` displays comprehensive, well-formatted help information\n55: \n56: ---\n57: \n58: ### Task 4: Implement Go binary build targets\n59: - [ ] Create build-go target to build all Go binaries\n60: - [ ] Create individual targets for each binary:\n61:   - `build-agentd` for cmd/agentd/main.go\n62:   - `build-picod` for cmd/picod/main.go\n63:   - `build-agentcube` for cmd/agentcube/main.go\n64:   - `build-code-interpreter` for cmd/code-interpreter/main.go\n65:   - `build-agent-runtime` for cmd/agent-runtime/main.go\n66:   - `build-agentcube-util` for cmd/agentcube-util/main.go\n67: - [ ] Use `go build` with proper flags (-ldflags for version info)\n68: - [ ] Set GOBIN to local build directory\n69: - [ ] Support platform builds (GOOS, GOARCH variables)\n70: - [ ] Support cross-compilation\n71: - [ ] Add build timestamp and git commit to binaries\n72: - [ ] Ensure build fails on errors\n73: - [ ] Test each individual binary build\n74: - [ ] Test `make build-go` builds all binaries\n75: \n76: **Verification**: All Go binaries build successfully with version information embedded\n77: \n78: ---\n79: \n80: ### Task 5: Implement Go build optimization targets\n81: - [ ] Create `build-go-race` target with race detector\n82: - [ ] Create `build-go-debug` target with debug symbols\n83: - [ ] Create `build-go-release` target with optimizations\n84: - [ ] Implement build caching support\n85: - [ ] Add parallel build support for multiple binaries\n86: - [ ] Create `build-go-fast` target that skips unnecessary steps\n87: - [ ] Support incremental builds\n88: - [ ] Add build time measurement\n89: - [ ] Test race detector builds\n90: - [ ] Test optimized release builds\n91: \n92: **Verification**: Optimized build targets work correctly and provide expected performance improvements\n93: \n94: ---\n95: \n96: ### Task 6: Implement Python SDK build targets\n97: - [ ] Create `build-python` target for Python SDK\n98: - [ ] Create `build-wheel` target to build .whl files\n99: - [ ] Create `build-sdist` target to build source distribution\n100: - [ ] Use `python -m build` for packaging\n101: - [ ] Configure output directory for Python packages\n102: - [ ] Support Python version specification (PYTHON_VERSION)\n103: - [ ] Add clean-python target for Python build artifacts\n104: - [ ] Verify package metadata in pyproject.toml\n105: - [ ] Test wheel building\n106: - [ ] Test source distribution building\n107: \n108: **Verification**: Python SDK builds successfully as wheel and source distribution\n109: \n110: ---\n111: \n112: ### Task 7: Implement Go unit test targets\n113: - [ ] Create `test-go` target to run all Go tests\n114: - [ ] Create individual test targets for each package:\n115:   - `test-agentd` for pkg/agentd\n116:   - `test-picod` for pkg/picod\n117:   - `test-router` for pkg/router\n118:   - `test-store` for pkg/store\n119:   - `test-workloadmanager` for pkg/workloadmanager\n120: - [ ] Support test verbosity (-v